    </item>
    <item>
      <title>On Screw Ups and Forgiveness</title>
      <link>http://www.alisonrothwell.com/surviving/screw-ups-forgiveness/</link>
      <comments>http://www.alisonrothwell.com/surviving/screw-ups-forgiveness/#comments</comments>
      <pubDate>Wed, 13 Oct 2010 08:25:00 +0000</pubDate>
      <dc:creator>SEO Alison</dc:creator>
      <category><![CDATA[Surviving]]></category>
      <category><![CDATA[email]]></category>
      <category><![CDATA[ezine]]></category>
      <category><![CDATA[screw ups]]></category>
      <guid isPermaLink="false">http://www.alisonrothwell.com/?p=1122</guid>
      <description><![CDATA[Last week I made a mistake. Of the technical error variety. Regular readers of my blog will have noticed that I have moved back to this domain recently. It was during the &#8220;house move&#8221; from blog to blog that the error occurred. Due to an unexpected connection (read completely undetected connection by myself) between my [...]]]></description>
      <content:encoded><![CDATA[<p></p>
<p><a title="Windows catastrophic failure" href="http://www.flickr.com/photos/42371658@N00/4989113047/" target="_blank"><img class="alignleft" src="http://farm5.static.flickr.com/4091/4989113047_bf7a7f45cf_m.jpg" border="0" alt="4989113047 bf7a7f45cf m On Screw Ups and Forgiveness"  title="On Screw Ups and Forgiveness" /></a>Last week I made a mistake. Of the technical error variety. Regular readers of my blog will have noticed that I have moved back to this domain recently. It was during the &#8220;house move&#8221; from blog to blog that the error occurred.</p>
<p>Due to an unexpected connection (read completely undetected connection by myself) between my mailing list software and the blog, I managed to email a couple of hundred people with an email that didn&#8217;t make sense. Eleven times.</p>
<p>First I knew of it was when I got a very kind email from an ezine subscriber letting me know of said email and its frequency. I rushed over to my mailing list website to look at the damage. Yes, the email had been sent, with the frequency the kind ezine reader had suggested. It was head in hands time.</p>
<p>You see, there&#8217;s nothing more galling than when you put yourself out there as someone who &#8220;understands geeky stuff&#8221; for an embarrassing incident of the geeky type to occur on your watch.</p>
<p>Thankfully, just a small list had been emailed &#8211; not everyone &#8211; the group of peeps who have been &#8220;with me&#8221; for the longest time. Still, I braced myself for the complaints &#8211; and the unsubscribes.</p>
<p>What the Frack were &#8220;they&#8221; going to think? Having got used to a weekly ezine with free stuff about online marketing, they were now the unwilling recipients of eleven &#8211; count &#8216;em &#8211; plain text emails containing an elderly blog post?</p>
<p>Truth was, only six people left the list. And then only three people emailed me to complain about the email itself &#8211; all three seemingly not spotting it was a mistake rather than my usual ezine. One even said she had to unsubscribe because I was emailing her too often (!)</p>
<p>Everyone else seemed to have had a good spirited chuckle at my calamity and had moved on.</p>
<p>So, although it seemed like a disaster of epic proportions to me, it didn&#8217;t seem to upset those that mattered the most, my regular ezine members. And after thinking about it for a little while, I kind of realized why this might be:</p>
<p>The readers had been with me for a long time. They were used to what my communications looked like (the free tips ezine) and how often they got them (weekly, on a Friday). Anything else didn&#8217;t seem right to them, so they put it down to a mistake and ignored it.</p>
<p>So, thanks to my &#8220;technical error&#8221; I&#8217;ve learnt that there&#8217;s another bonus to having a regular, consistent approach to my online communications. A more forgiving audience when you screw things up <img src='http://www.alisonrothwell.com/wp-includes/images/smilies/icon_smile.gif' alt="icon smile On Screw Ups and Forgiveness" class='wp-smiley' title="On Screw Ups and Forgiveness" /> </p>
<p><small><a title="Attribution-NoDerivs License" href="http://creativecommons.org/licenses/by-nd/2.0/" target="_blank"><img src="../wp-content/plugins/photo-dropper/images/cc.png" border="0" alt="cc On Screw Ups and Forgiveness" width="16" height="16" align="absmiddle" title="On Screw Ups and Forgiveness" /></a> <a href="http://www.photodropper.com/photos/" target="_blank">photo</a> credit: <a title="tony_the_bald_eagle" href="http://www.flickr.com/photos/42371658@N00/4989113047/" target="_blank">tony_the_bald_eagle</a></small></p>

]]></content:encoded>
      <wfw:commentRss>http://www.alisonrothwell.com/surviving/screw-ups-forgiveness/feed/</wfw:commentRss>
      <slash:comments>0</slash:comments>
    </item>
